<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p>Have you ever tried to predict the future? What lies ahead is a mystery which is usually only solved by waiting. In this course, you will stop waiting and learn to use the powerful ARIMA class models to forecast the future. You will learn how to use the statsmodels package to analyze time series, to build tailored models, and to forecast under uncertainty. How will the stock market move in the next 24 hours? How will the levels of CO2 change in the next decade? How many earthquakes will there be next year? You will learn to solve all these problems and more.</p>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="ARMA-Models">ARMA Models<a class="anchor-link" href="#ARMA-Models"> </a></h2><blockquote><p>Dive straight in and learn about the most important properties of time series. You'll learn about stationarity and how this is important for ARMA models. You'll learn how to test for stationarity by eye and with a standard statistical test. Finally, you'll learn the basic structure of ARMA models and use this to generate some ARMA data and fit an ARMA model.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id="Intro-to-time-series-and-stationarity">Intro to time series and stationarity<a class="anchor-link" href="#Intro-to-time-series-and-stationarity"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Exploration</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>You may make plots regularly, but in this course, it is important that you can explicitly control which axis different time series are plotted on. This will be important so you can evaluate your time series predictions later.</p>
<p>Here your task is to plot a dataset of monthly US candy production between 1972 and 2018.</p>
<p>Specifically, you are plotting the industrial production index IPG3113N. This is total amount of sugar and confectionery products produced in the USA per month, as a percentage of the January 2012 production. So 120 would be 120% of the January 2012 industrial production.</p>
<p>Check out how this quantity has changed over time and how it changes throughout the year.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Import matplotlib.pyplot giving it the alias plt and import pandas giving it the alias pd.</li>
<li>Load in the candy production time series 'candy_production.csv' using pandas, set the index to the'date'column, parse the dates and assign it to the variable candy.</li>
<li>Plot the time series onto the axis ax1 using the DataFrame's .plot() method. Then show the plot.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">

<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.pyplot</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">plt</span>

<span class="c1"># Load in the time series</span>
<span class="n">candy</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;./datasets/candy_production.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;date&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot and show the time series on axis ax1</span>

<span class="n">candy</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>This plotting method will be invaluable later when plotting multiple things on the same axis! Can you tell whether this is a stationary time series or not? How does it change throughout the years?</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Train-test splits</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In this exercise you are going to take the candy production dataset and split it into a train and a test set. Like you understood in the video exercise, the reason to do this is so that you can test the quality of your model fit when you are done.</p>
<p>The candy production data set has been loaded in for you as candy already and pyplot has been loaded in as plt.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Split the time series into train and test sets by slicing with datetime indexes. Take the train set as everything up to the end of 2006 and the test set as everything from the start of 2007.</li>
<li>Make a pyplot axes using the subplots() function.</li>
<li>Use the DataFrame's .plot() method to plot the train and test sets on the axis ax.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">

<span class="n">candy_test</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">candy</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;2007&#39;</span><span class="p">:]</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot the train and test sets on the axis ax</span>

<span class="n">candy_test</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">)</span>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Take a look at the plot, do you think that you yourself could predict what happens after 2006 given the blue training set. What happens to the long term trend and the seasonal pattern?</p>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Is it stationary</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Identifying whether a time series is stationary or non-stationary is very important. If it is stationary you can use ARMA models to predict the next values of the time series. If it is non-stationary then you cannot use ARMA models, however, as you will see in the next lesson, you can often transform non-stationary time series to stationary ones.</p>
<p>In this exercise you will examine some stock and earthquake data sets in order to identify which are ready for ARMA modeling, and which will need further work to make them stationary.</p>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/download.svg" alt=""></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ol>
<li><p>The top plot shown is a time series of Amazon stock close price.
Is the stock close price stationary?</p>
<p>Ans: No, because the top plot has a trend.</p>
</li>
<li><p>The middle plot shown is a time series of the return (percentage increase of price per day) of Amazon stock.
Is the stock return stationary?</p>
<p>Ans: No, because in the middle plot, the variance changes with time.</p>
</li>
<li><p>The bottom plot is a time series of the number of major earthquakes per year (earthquakes of magnitude 7.0 or greater).
Is the number of major earthquakes per year stationary?</p>
<p>Ans: Yes, the bottom plot appears to be stationary.</p>
<p>You can't see any trend, or any obvious changes in variance, or dynamics. This time series looks stationary.</p>
</li>
</ol>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Making-time-series-stationary">Making time series stationary<a class="anchor-link" href="#Making-time-series-stationary"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Augmented Dicky-Fuller</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In this exercise you will run the augmented Dicky-Fuller test on the earthquakes time series to test for stationarity. You plotted this time series in the last exercise. It looked like it could be stationary, but earthquakes are very damaging. If you want to make predictions about them you better be sure.</p>
<p>Remember that if it were not stationary this would mean that the number of earthquakes per year has a trend and is changing. This would be terrible news if it is trending upwards, as it means more damage. It would also be terrible news if it were trending downwards, it might suggest the core of our planet is changing and this could have lots of knock on effects for us!</p>
<p>The earthquakes DataFrame has been loaded in for you as earthquake.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Import the augmented Dicky-Fuller function adfuller() from statsmodels.</li>
<li>Run the adfuller() function on the 'earthquakes_per_year' column of the earthquake DataFrame and assign the result to result.</li>
<li>Print the test statistic, the p-value and the critical values.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">earthquake</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;./datasets/earthquakes.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">usecols</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;date&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;earthquakes_per_year&#39;</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;date&#39;</span><span class="p">])</span>
<span class="n">display</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">earthquake</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">


<div class="output_html rendered_html output_subarea ">
<div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.tsa.stattools</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">adfuller</span>

<span class="c1"># Run test</span>
<span class="n">result</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">adfuller</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">earthquake</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;earthquakes_per_year&#39;</span><span class="p">])</span>

<span class="c1"># Print test statistic</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">result</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">])</span>

</pre></div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Earth shaking effort! You can reject the null hypothesis that the time series is non-stationary. Therefore it is stationary. You probably could have intuited this from looking at the graph or by knowing a little about geology. The time series covers only about 100 years which is a very short time on a geological time scale.</p>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Taking the difference</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In this exercise, you will to prepare a time series of the population of a city for modeling. If you could predict the growth rate of a city then it would be possible to plan and build the infrastructure that the city will need later, thus future-proofing public spending. In this case the time series is fictitious but its perfect to practice on.</p>
<p>You will test for stationarity by eye and use the Augmented Dicky-Fuller test, and take the difference to make the dataset stationary.</p>
<p>The DataFrame of the time series has been loaded in for you as city and the adfuller() function has been imported.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Run the augmented Dicky-Fuller on the 'city_population' column of city.</li>
<li>Print the test statistic and the p-value.</li>
<li>Take the first difference of city dropping the NaN values. Assign this to city_stationary and run the test again.</li>
<li>Take the second difference of city, by applying the .diff() method twice and drop the NaN values.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">

<span class="n">city</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">()</span>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Other tranforms</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Differencing should be the first transform you try to make a time series stationary. But sometimes it isn't the best option.</p>
<p>A classic way of transforming stock time series is the log-return of the series. This is calculated as follows:$$ \text{log\_return}(y_t) = \log \big(\frac{y_t}{y_{t-1}}\big) $$
You can calculate the log-return of this DataFrame by substituting:</p>
<p>$y_t$  amazon</p>
<p>$y_{t-1}$  amazon.shift(1)</p>
<p>$\log()$  <code>np.log()</code></p>
<p>In this exercise you will compare the log-return transform and the first order difference of the Amazon stock time series to find which is better for making the time series stationary.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<span class="n">amazon</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">()</span>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">amazon_diff</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">amazon</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diff</span><span class="p">()</span>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Intro-to-AR,-MA-and-ARMA-models">Intro to AR, MA and ARMA models<a class="anchor-link" href="#Intro-to-AR,-MA-and-ARMA-models"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Model order</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>When fitting and working with AR, MA and ARMA models it is very important to understand the model order. You will need to pick the model order when fitting. Picking this correctly will give you a better fitting model which makes better predictions. So in this section you will practice working with model order.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li><p>Print ar_coefs and ma_coefs which are available in the console. If you were to use these in the arma_generate_sample() function what would be the order of the data?</p>

<pre><code>python:
  print(ar_coefs)
  [1, 0.4, -0.1]

  print(ma_coefs)
  [1, 0.2]</code></pre>
<p><strong>Ans:</strong> ARMA(2,1)</p>
</li>
<li><p>Print ar_coefs and ma_coefs which are available in the console. If you were to use these in the arma_generate_sample() function what would the lag-1 AR coefficient?</p>
<p><strong>Ans:</strong> -0.4</p>
</li>
<li><p>Which of these models is equivalent to an AR(1) model?</p>
<p><strong>Ans:</strong> ARMA(1,0)</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Note that setting either p or q to zero means we get a simpler model, either a AR or MA model.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Generating ARMA data</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In this exercise you will generate 100 days worth of AR/MA/ARMA data. Remember that in the real world applications, this data could be changes in Google stock prices, the energy requirements of New York City, or the number of cases of flu.</p>
<p>You can use the arma_generate_sample() function available in your workspace to generate time series using different AR and MA coefficients.</p>
<p>Remember for any model ARMA(p,q):<br></p>
<ul>
<li>The list ar_coefs has the form [1, -a_1, -a_2, ..., -a_p].</li>
<li>The list ma_coefs has the form [1, m_1, m_2, ..., m_q],</li>
</ul>
<p>where a_i are the lag-i AR coefficients and m_j are the lag-j MA coefficients.</p>
<p>Instructions: <br></p>
<ul>
<li>Set <strong>ar_coefs</strong> and <strong>ma_coefs</strong> for an MA(1) model with MA lag-1 coefficient of -0.7.</li>
<li>Generate a time series of 100 values.</li>
<li>Set the coefficients for an AR(2) model with AR lag-1 and lag-2 coefficients of 0.3 and 0.2 respectively.</li>
<li>Set the coefficients for a model with form $ y_t = -0.2 y_{t-1} + 0.3 \epsilon_{t-1} + 0.4 \epsilon_{t-2} + \epsilon_{t}$</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.tsa.arima_process</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">arma_generate_sample</span>
<span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">random</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">seed</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Set coefficients</span>
<span class="n">ar_coefs</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">ma_coefs</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="o">-</span><span class="mf">0.7</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># Generate data</span>
<span class="n">y</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">arma_generate_sample</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ar_coefs</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ma_coefs</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">nsample</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">100</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">scale</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.5</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ylabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="sa">r</span><span class="s1">&#39;$y_t$&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="sa">r</span><span class="s1">&#39;$t$&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">



<div class="output_png output_subarea ">
<img src="data:image/png;base64,"
>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>You can use this data to check our code. If you can recover these same coefficients when you fit a model, then you will know your methods work!</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Fitting Prelude</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Great, you understand model order! Understanding the order is important when it comes to fitting models. You will always need to select the order of model you fit to your data, no matter what that data is.</p>
<p>In this exercise you will do some basic fitting. Fitting models is the next key step towards making predictions. We'll go into this more in the next chapter but let's get a head start.</p>
<p>Some example ARMA(1,1) data have been created and are available in your environment as y. This data could represent the amount of traffic congestion. You could use forecasts of this to suggest the efficient routes for drivers.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Import the ARMA model class from the statsmodels.tsa.arima_model submodule.</li>
<li>Create a model object, passing it the time series y and the model order (1,1). Assign this to the variable model.</li>
<li>Use the model's .fit() method to fit to the data.</li>
</ul>
<p>CODE:</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Import the ARMA model</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.tsa.arima_model</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">ARMA</span>

<span class="c1"># Instantiate the model</span>
<span class="n">model</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ARMA</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">order</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="c1"># Fit the model</span>
<span class="n">results</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Fitting-the-Future">Fitting the Future<a class="anchor-link" href="#Fitting-the-Future"> </a></h2><blockquote><p>What lies ahead in this chapter is you predicting what lies ahead in your data. You'll learn how to use the elegant statsmodels package to fit ARMA, ARIMA and ARMAX models. Then you'll use your models to predict the uncertain future of stock prices!</p>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Fitting-time-series-models">Fitting time series models<a class="anchor-link" href="#Fitting-time-series-models"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Fitting AR and MA models</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In this exercise you will fit an AR and an MA model to some data. The data here has been generated using the arma_generate_sample() function we used before.</p>
<p>You know the real AR and MA parameters used to create this data so it is a really good way to gain some confidence with ARMA models and know you are doing it right. In the next exercise you'll move onto some real world data with confidence.</p>
<p>There is a pandas DataFrame available in your environment called sample. It has two columns of different time series data.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br>
Using the information in the summary printed, which of the following set of parameters do you think was used to generate the 'timeseries_1' data?</p>
<p>Possible Answers</p>
<ul>
<li><p>ar_coefs = [0.9, 0.3],<br>
ma_coefs = [1]</p>
</li>
<li><p>ar_coefs = [1] ,<br>
ma_coefs = [1, -0.9, 0.3]</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>ar_coefs = [1, -0.9, 0.3],<br>
ma_coefs = [1]</strong></p>
</li>
<li><p>ar_coefs = [1, 0.9, -0.3],<br>
ma_coefs = [1]</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Previous Code Version:</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.tsa.arima_model</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">ARMA</span>

<span class="c1"># Instantiate the model</span>
<span class="n">model</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ARMA</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">sample</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;timeseries_1&#39;</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">order</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="c1"># Fit the model</span>
<span class="n">results</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Print summary</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">summary</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Fitting an ARMA model</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In this exercise you will fit an ARMA model to the earthquakes dataset. You saw before that the earthquakes dataset is stationary so you don't need to transform it at all. It comes ready for modeling straight out the ground. You can remind yourself what it looks like below.</p>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/earthquakes.png" alt=""></p>
<p>The earthquakes dataset is available in your environment as earthquake. The ARMA class is also available in your environment.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Instantiate an ARMA(3,1) model and pass it the earthquakes dataset.</li>
<li>Fit the model.</li>
<li>Print the summary of the model fit.</li>
</ul>
<p>Previous version Code:</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Instantiate the model</span>
<span class="n">model</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ARMA</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">earthquake</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;earthquakes_per_year&#39;</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">order</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="c1"># Fit the model</span>
<span class="n">results</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Print model fit summary</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">summary</span><span class="p">())</span>

<blockquote><p><strong>Fitting an ARMAX model</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In this exercise you will fit an ARMAX model to a time series which represents the wait times at an accident and emergency room for urgent medical care.</p>
<p>The variable you would like to model is the wait times to be seen by a medical professional wait_times_hrs. This may be related to an exogenous variable that you measured nurse_count which is the number of nurses on shift at any given time. These can be seen below.</p>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/exog_time_series.png" alt=""></p>
<p>This is a particularly interesting case of time series modeling as, if the number of nurses has an effect, you could change this to affect the wait times.</p>
<p>The time series data is available in your environment as hospital and has the two columns mentioned above. The ARMA class is also available for you.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Instantiate an ARMAX(2,1) model to train on the 'wait_times_hrs' column of hospital using the 'nurse_count' column as an exogenous variable.</li>
<li>Fit the model.</li>
<li>Print the summary of the model fit.</li>
</ul>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Forecasting">Forecasting<a class="anchor-link" href="#Forecasting"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Generating one-step-ahead predictions</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>It is very hard to forecast stock prices. Classic economics actually tells us that this should be impossible because of market clearing.</p>
<p>Your task in this exercise is to attempt the impossible and predict the Amazon stock price anyway.</p>
<p>In this exercise you will generate one-step-ahead predictions for the stock price as well as the uncertainty of these predictions.</p>
<p>A model has already been fitted to the Amazon data for you. The results object from this model is available in your environment as results.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Use the results object to make one-step-ahead predictions over the latest 30 days of data and assign the result to one_step_forecast.</li>
<li>Assign your mean predictions to mean_forecast using one of the attributes of the one_step_forecast object.</li>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">amazon</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;./datasets/amazon_close.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;date&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">amazon</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">amazon</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[::</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">SARIMAX</span>

                <span class="n">enforce_invertibility</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">,</span>
                <span class="n">enforce_stationarity</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">,</span>
                <span class="n">simple_differencing</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">,</span> 
                <span class="n">measurement_error</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">,</span>
                <span class="n">k_trend</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">results</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

<p>The predictions told me you could do it! You can use theis one-step-ahead forecast to estimate what your error would be, if you were to make a prediction for the Amazon stock price of tomorrow.</p>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Plotting one-step-ahead predictions</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Now that you have your predictions on the Amazon stock, you should plot these predictions to see how you've done.</p>
<p>You made predictions over the latest 30 days of data available, always forecasting just one day ahead. By evaluating these predictions you can judge how the model performs in making predictions for just the next day, where you don't know the answer.</p>
<p>The lower_limits, upper_limits and amazon DataFrames as well as your mean prediction mean_forecast that you created in the last exercise are available in your environment.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Plot the amazon data, using the amazon.index as the x coordinates.</li>
<li>Plot the mean_forecast prediction similarly, using mean_forecast.index as the x-coordinates.</li>
<li>Plot a shaded area between lower_limits and upper_limits of your confidence interval. Use the index of lower_limits as the x coordinates.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">amazon</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">amazon</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;close&#39;</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;observed&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot your mean predictions</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mean_forecast</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">mean_forecast</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;r&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;forecast&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># shade the area between your confidence limits</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fill_between</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">lower_limits</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">lower_limits</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">upper_limits</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;pink&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># set labels, legends and show plot</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;Date&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ylabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;Amazon Stock Price - Close USD&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Generating dynamic forecasts</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Now lets move a little further into the future, to dynamic predictions. What if you wanted to predict the Amazon stock price, not just for tomorrow, but for next week or next month? This is where dynamical predictions come in.</p>
<p>Remember that in the video you learned how it is more difficult to make precise long-term forecasts because the shock terms add up. The further into the future the predictions go, the more uncertain. This is especially true with stock data and so you will likely find that your predictions in this exercise are not as precise as those in the last exercise.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Use the results object to make a dynamic predictions for the latest 30 days and assign the result to dynamic_forecast.</li>
<li>Assign your predictions to a new variable called mean_forecast using one of the attributes of the dynamic_forecast object.</li>
<li>Extract the confidence intervals of your predictions from the dynamic_forecast object and assign them to a new variable confidence_intervals.</li>
<li>Print your mean predictions.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">dynamic_forecast</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_prediction</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">start</span><span class="o">=-</span><span class="mi">30</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">dynamic</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Extract prediction mean</span>
<span class="n">mean_forecast</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">dynamic_forecast</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predicted_mean</span>

<span class="c1"># Get confidence intervals of predictions</span>
<span class="n">confidence_intervals</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">dynamic_forecast</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">conf_int</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Select lower and upper confidence limits</span>
<span class="n">lower_limits</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">confidence_intervals</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[:,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;lower close&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">upper_limits</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">confidence_intervals</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[:,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;upper close&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># Print bet estimate predictions</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mean_forecast</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">values</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fill_between</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">lower_limits</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">lower_limits</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">upper_limits</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;pink&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># set labels, legends and show plot</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;Date&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ylabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;Amazon Stock Price - Close USD&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Intro-to-ARIMA-models">Intro to ARIMA models<a class="anchor-link" href="#Intro-to-ARIMA-models"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Differencing and fitting ARMA</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In this exercise you will fit an ARMA model to the Amazon stocks dataset. As you saw before, this is a non-stationary dataset. You will use differencing to make it stationary so that you can fit an ARMA model.</p>
<p>In the next section you'll make a forecast of the differences and use this to forecast the actual values.</p>
<p>The Amazon stock time series in available in your environment as amazon. The SARIMAX model class is also available in your environment.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Use the .diff() method of amazon to make the time series stationary by taking the first difference. Don't forget to drop the NaN values using the .dropna() method.</li>
<li>Create an ARMA(2,2) model using the SARIMAX class, passing it the stationary data.</li>
<li>Fit the model.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">

<span class="n">display</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">amazon</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">())</span>
<span class="n">amazon</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sort_index</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">inplace</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">display</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">amazon</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">())</span>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Unrolling ARMA forecast</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Now you will use the model that you trained in the previous exercise arma in order to forecast the absolute value of the Amazon stocks dataset. Remember that sometimes predicting the difference could be enough; will the stocks go up, or down; but sometimes the absolute value is key.</p>
<p>The results object from the model you trained in the last exercise is available in your environment as arma_results. The np.cumsum() function and the original DataFrame amazon are also available.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Use the .get_forecast() method of the arma_results object and select the predicted mean of the next 10 differences.</li>
<li>Use the np.cumsum() function to integrate your difference forecast.</li>
<li>Add the last value of the original DataFrame to make your forecast an absolute value.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">arma_diff_forecast</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">arma_results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_forecast</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">steps</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predicted_mean</span>

<span class="c1"># Integrate the difference forecast</span>
<span class="n">arma_int_forecast</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">cumsum</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">arma_diff_forecast</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Make absolute value forecast</span>
<span class="n">arma_value_forecast</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">arma_int_forecast</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">amazon</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># Print forecast</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">arma_value_forecast</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>You have just made an ARIMA forecast the hard way. Next you'll use statsmodels to make things easier.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Fitting an ARIMA model</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In this exercise you'll learn how to be lazy in time series modeling. Instead of taking the difference, modeling the difference and then integrating, you're just going to lets statsmodels do the hard work for you.</p>
<p>You'll repeat the same exercise that you did before, of forecasting the absolute values of the Amazon stocks dataset, but this time with an ARIMA model.</p>
<p>A subset of the stocks dataset is available in your environment as amazon and so is the SARIMAX model class.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Create an ARIMA(2,1,2) model, using the SARIMAX class, passing it the Amazon stocks data amazon.</li>
<li>Fit the model.</li>
<li>Make a forecast of mean values of the Amazon data for the next 10 time steps. Assign the result to arima_value_forecast.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">arima</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">SARIMAX</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">amazon</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">order</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="c1"># Fit ARIMA model</span>
<span class="n">arima_results</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">arima</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Make ARIMA forecast of next 10 values</span>
<span class="n">arima_value_forecast</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">arima_results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_forecast</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">steps</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predicted_mean</span>

<span class="c1"># Print forecast</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">arima_value_forecast</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_area">

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>You just made the same forecast you made before, but this time with an ARIMA model. Your two forecasts give the same results, but the ARIMA forecast was a lot easier to code!</p>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Choosing ARIMA model</strong></p>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="The-Best-of-the-Best-Models">The Best of the Best Models<a class="anchor-link" href="#The-Best-of-the-Best-Models"> </a></h2><blockquote><p>In this chapter, you will become a modeler of discerning taste. You'll learn how to identify promising model orders from the data itself, then, once the most promising models have been trained, you'll learn how to choose the best model from this fitted selection. You'll also learn a great framework for structuring your time series projects.</p>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Intro-to-ACF-and-PACF">Intro to ACF and PACF<a class="anchor-link" href="#Intro-to-ACF-and-PACF"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>AR or MA</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In this exercise you will use the ACF and PACF to decide whether some data is best suited to an MA model or an AR model. Remember that selecting the right model order is of great importance to our predictions.</p>
<p>Remember that for different types of models we expect the following behavior in the ACF and PACF:<br></p>
<table>
<thead><tr>
<th></th>
<th>AR(p)</th>
<th>MA(q)</th>
<th>ARMA(p,q)</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>ACF</td>
<td>Tails off</td>
<td>Cuts off after lag q</td>
<td>Tails off</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>PACF</td>
<td>Cuts off after lag p</td>
<td>Tails off</td>
<td>Tails off</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><br></p>
<p>A time series with unknown properties, df is available for you in your environment.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Import the plot_acf and plot_pacf functions from statsmodels.</li>
<li>Plot the ACF and the PACF for the series df for the first 10 lags but not the zeroth lag.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;./datasets/download.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">])</span>
<span class="n">df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">asfreq</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;d&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">plot_acf</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">plot_pacf</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot the ACF of df</span>
<span class="n">plot_acf</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">lags</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">zero</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">auto_ylims</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot the PACF of df</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Create and train a model object for the earthquakes time series.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">SARIMAX</span>
<span class="c1"># Create figure</span>
<span class="n">fig</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax2</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot ACF and PACF</span>
<span class="n">plot_acf</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">earthquake</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">lags</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">zero</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plot_pacf</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">earthquake</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">lags</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">zero</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax2</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Show plot</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Instantiate model</span>
<span class="n">model</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">SARIMAX</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">earthquake</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">order</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="c1"># Train model</span>
<span class="n">results</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Intro-to-AIC-and-BIC">Intro to AIC and BIC<a class="anchor-link" href="#Intro-to-AIC-and-BIC"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Searching over model order</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In this exercise you are faced with a dataset which appears to be an ARMA model. You can see the ACF and PACF in the plot below. In order to choose the best order for this model you are going to have to do a search over lots of potential model orders to find the best set.</p>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/unclear_PACF.png" alt=""></p>
<p>The SARIMAX model class and the time series DataFrame df are available in your environment.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Loop over values of p from 0-2.</li>
<li>Loop over values of q from 0-2.</li>
<li>Train and fit an ARMA(p,q) model.</li>
<li>Append a tuple of (p,q, AIC value, BIC value) to order_aic_bic.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;./datasets/df_500.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">])</span>
<span class="n">df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">asfreq</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;d&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>&lt;class &#39;pandas.core.frame.DataFrame&#39;&gt;
DatetimeIndex: 500 entries, 2013-01-01 to 2014-05-15
Freq: D
Data columns (total 1 columns):
 #   Column  Non-Null Count  Dtype  
---  ------  --------------  -----  
 0   y       500 non-null    float64
dtypes: float64(1)
memory usage: 7.8 KB
</pre>
</div>
</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">order_aic_bic</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[]</span>

<span class="c1"># Loop over p values from 0-2</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">p</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="c1"># Loop over q values from 0-2</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">q</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="c1"># Create and fit ARMA(p, q) model</span>
        <span class="n">model</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">SARIMAX</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">order</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">p</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">q</span><span class="p">))</span>
        <span class="n">results</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>
        
        <span class="c1"># Append order and results tuple</span>
        <span class="n">order_aic_bic</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="n">p</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">q</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">aic</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">bic</span><span class="p">))</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>You built 9 models in just a few seconds! In the next exercise you will evaluate the results to choose the best model.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Choosing order with AIC and BIC</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Now that you have performed a search over many model orders, you will evaluate your results to find the best model order.</p>
<p>The list of tuples of (p,q, AIC value, BIC value) that you created in the last exercise, order_aic_bic, is available in your environment. pandas has also been imported as pd.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Create a DataFrame to hold the order search information in the order_aic_bic list. Give it the column names ['p', 'q', 'AIC', 'BIC'].</li>
<li>Print the DataFrame in order of increasing AIC and then BIC.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">order_df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">order_aic_bic</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">columns</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;p&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;q&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;AIC&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;BIC&#39;</span><span class="p">])</span>

<span class="c1"># Print order_df in order of increasing AIC</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">order_df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sort_values</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;AIC&#39;</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="c1"># Print order_df in order of increasing BIC</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">order_df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sort_values</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;BIC&#39;</span><span class="p">))</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Which of the following models is the best fit?</p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> ARMA(2,1)</p>
<p>This time AIC and BIC favored the same model, but this won't always be the case.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>AIC and BIC vs ACF and PACF</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In this exercise you will apply an AIC-BIC order search for the earthquakes time series. In the last lesson you decided that this dataset looked like an AR(1) process. You will do a grid search over parameters to see if you get the same results. The ACF and PACF plots for this dataset are shown below.</p>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/earthquakes_pacf.png" alt=""></p>
<p>The SARIMAX model class and the time series DataFrame earthquake are available in your environment.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Loop over orders of p and q between 0 and 2.</li>
<li>Inside the loop try to fit an ARMA(p,q) to earthquake on each loop.</li>
<li>Print p and q alongside AIC and BIC in each loop.</li>
<li>If the model fitting procedure fails print p, q, None, None.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">p</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">q</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="k">try</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="c1"># Create and fit ARMA(p, q) model</span>
            <span class="n">model</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">SARIMAX</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">earthquake</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">order</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">p</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">q</span><span class="p">))</span>
            <span class="n">results</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>
            
            <span class="c1"># Print order and results</span>
            <span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">p</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">q</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">aic</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">bic</span><span class="p">)</span>
            
        <span class="k">except</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">p</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">q</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">)</span>    
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

</pre>

</div>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Super! If you look at your printed results you will see that the AIC and BIC both actually favor an ARMA(1,1) model. This isn't what you predicted from the ACF and PACF but notice that the lag 2-3 PACF values are very close to significant, so the ACF/PACF are close to those of an ARMA(p,q) model.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Model-diagnostics">Model diagnostics<a class="anchor-link" href="#Model-diagnostics"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Mean absolute error</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Obviously, before you use the model to predict, you want to know how accurate your predictions are. The mean absolute error (MAE) is a good statistic for this. It is the mean difference between your predictions and the true values.</p>
<p>In this exercise you will calculate the MAE for an ARMA(1,1) model fit to the earthquakes time series</p>
<p>numpy has been imported into your environment as np and the earthquakes time series is available for you as earthquake.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Use np functions to calculate the Mean Absolute Error (MAE) of the .resid attribute of the results object.</li>
<li>Print the MAE.</li>
<li>Use the DataFrame's .plot() method with no arguments to plot the earthquake time series.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">model</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">SARIMAX</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">earthquake</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">order</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">results</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Calculate the mean absolute error from residuals</span>
<span class="n">mae</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">abs</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resid</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="c1"># Print mean absolute error</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mae</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Make plot of time series for comparison</span>
<span class="n">earthquake</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>4.755625669976196
</pre>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_area">



<div class="output_png output_subarea ">
<img src="data:image/png;base64,"
>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Great! Your mean error is about 4-5 earthquakes per year. You have plotted the time series so that you can see how the MAE compares to the spread of the time series. Considering that there are about 20 earthquakes per year that is not too bad.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Diagnostic summary statistics</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>It is important to know when you need to go back to the drawing board in model design. In this exercise you will use the residual test statistics in the results summary to decide whether a model is a good fit to a time series.</p>
<p>Here is a reminder of the tests in the model summary:<br></p>

<th>Test</th>
<th>Null hypothesis</th>
<th>P-value name</th>
</tr>
</thead>

<tr>
<td>Ljung-Box</td>
<td>There are no correlations in the residual</td>
<td>Prob(Q)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Jarque-Bera</td>
<td>The residuals are normally distributed</td>
<td>Prob(JB)</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>An unknown time series df and the SARIMAX model class are available for you in your environment.</p>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Box-Jenkins-method">Box-Jenkins method<a class="anchor-link" href="#Box-Jenkins-method"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In the following exercises you will apply to the Box-Jenkins methodology to go from an unknown dataset to a model which is ready to make forecasts.</p>
<p>You will be using a new time series. This is the personal savings as % of disposable income 1955-1979 in the US.</p>
<p>The first step of the Box-Jenkins methodology is Identification. In this exercise you will use the tools at your disposal to test whether this new time series is stationary.</p>
<p>The time series has been loaded in as a DataFrame savings and the adfuller() function has been imported.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Plot the time series using the DataFrame's .plot() method.</li>
<li>Apply the Dicky-Fuller test to the 'savings' column of the savings DataFrame and assign the test outcome to result.</li>
<li>Print the Dicky-Fuller test statistics and the associated p-value.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.tsa.stattools</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">adfuller</span>

<span class="n">savings</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;./datasets/savings.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">])</span>
<span class="n">savings</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>&lt;class &#39;pandas.core.frame.DataFrame&#39;&gt;
DatetimeIndex: 102 entries, 1955-01-01 to 1980-04-01
Data columns (total 1 columns):
 #   Column   Non-Null Count  Dtype  
---  ------   --------------  -----  
 0   savings  102 non-null    float64
dtypes: float64(1)
memory usage: 1.6 KB
</pre>
</div>
</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Plot time series</span>
<span class="n">savings</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Run Dicky-Fuller test</span>
<span class="n">result</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">adfuller</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">savings</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;savings&#39;</span><span class="p">])</span>

<span class="c1"># Print test statistics</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">result</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">])</span>

<span class="c1"># Print p-value</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">result</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">])</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">



<div class="output_png output_subarea ">

>
</div>

</div>

<div class="output_area">
