0.020815541644114133
</pre>
</div>
</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The Dicky-Fuller test says that the series is stationary. You can confirm this when you look at the plot. There is one fairly high value is 1976 which might be anomalous, but you will leave that for now.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Identification II</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>You learned that the savings time series is stationary without differencing. Now that you have this information you can try and identify what order of model will be the best fit.</p>
<p>The plot_acf() and the plot_pacf() functions have been imported and the time series has been loaded into the DataFrame savings.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Make a plot of the ACF, for lags 1-10 and plot it on axis ax1.</li>
<li>Do the same for the PACF.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">savings</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>&lt;class &#39;pandas.core.frame.DataFrame&#39;&gt;
DatetimeIndex: 102 entries, 1955-01-01 to 1980-04-01
Data columns (total 1 columns):
 #   Column   Non-Null Count  Dtype  
---  ------   --------------  -----  
 0   savings  102 non-null    float64
dtypes: float64(1)
memory usage: 1.6 KB
None
</pre>
</div>
</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">fig</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax2</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">))</span>
 
<span class="c1"># Plot the ACF of savings on ax1</span>
<span class="n">plot_acf</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">savings</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">lags</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">zero</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">auto_ylims</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot the PACF of savings on ax2</span>
<span class="n">plot_pacf</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">savings</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">lags</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">zero</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">auto_ylims</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">



<div class="output_png output_subarea ">
<img src="data:image/png;base64,"
>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Step one complete! The ACF and the PACF are a little inconclusive for this ones. The ACF tails off nicely but the PACF might be tailing off or it might be dropping off. So it could be an ARMA(p,q) model or a AR(p) model.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Estimation</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In the last exercise, the ACF and PACF were a little inconclusive. The results suggest your data could be an ARMA(p,q) model or could be an imperfect AR(3) model. In this exercise you will search over models over some model orders to find the best one according to AIC.</p>
<p>The time series savings has been loaded and the SARIMAX class has been imported into your environment.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Loop over values of p from 0 to 3 and values of q from 0 to 3.</li>
<li>Inside the loop, create an ARMA(p,q) model with a constant trend.</li>
<li>Then fit the model to the time series savings.</li>
<li>At the end of each loop print the values of p and q and the AIC and BIC.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">p</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">):</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># Loop over q values from 0-3</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">q</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="k">try</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="c1"># Create and fit ARMA(p, q) model</span>
            <span class="n">model</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">SARIMAX</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">savings</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">order</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">p</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">q</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">trend</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;c&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
            <span class="n">results</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>
            
            <span class="c1"># Print p, q, AIC, BIC</span>
            <span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">p</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">q</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">aic</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">bic</span><span class="p">)</span>
        <span class="k">except</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">p</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">q</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>0 0 313.6028657326894 318.85281135925794
0 1 267.0697097688693 274.9446282087221

</div>
</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Step two complete! You didn't store and sort your results this time. But the AIC and BIC both picked the ARMA(1,2) model as the best and the AR(3) model as the second best.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Diagnostics</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>You have arrived at the model diagnostic stage. So far you have found that the initial time series was stationary, but may have one outlying point. You identified promising model orders using the ACF and PACF and confirmed these insights by training a lot of models and using the AIC and BIC.</p>
<p>You found that the ARMA(1,2) model was the best fit to our data and now you want to check over the predictions it makes before you would move it into production.</p>
<p>The time series savings has been loaded and the SARIMAX class has been imported into your environment.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Retrain the ARMA(1,2) model on the time series, setting the trend to constant.</li>
<li>Create the 4 standard diagnostics plots.</li>
<li>Print the model residual summary statistics.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">model</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">SARIMAX</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">savings</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">order</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">trend</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;c&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">results</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Create the 4 diagnostics plots</span>
<span class="n">results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_diagnostics</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">20</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">));</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tight_layout</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Print summary</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">summary</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Great! The JB p-value is zero, which means you should reject the null hypothesis that the residuals are normally distributed. However, the histogram and Q-Q plots show that the residuals look normal. This time the JB value was thrown off by the one outlying point in the time series. In this case, you could go back and apply some transformation to remove this outlier or you probably just continue to the production stage.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Seasonal-ARIMA-Models">Seasonal ARIMA Models<a class="anchor-link" href="#Seasonal-ARIMA-Models"> </a></h2><blockquote><p>In this final chapter, you'll learn how to use seasonal ARIMA models to fit more complex data. You'll learn how to decompose this data into seasonal and non-seasonal parts and then you'll get the chance to utilize all your ARIMA tools on one last global forecast challenge.</p>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Seasonal-time-series">Seasonal time series<a class="anchor-link" href="#Seasonal-time-series"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Seasonal decompose</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>You can think of a time series as being composed of trend, seasonal and residual components. This can be a good way to think about the data when you go about modeling it. If you know the period of the time series you can decompose it into these components.</p>
<p>In this exercise you will decompose a time series showing the monthly milk production per cow in the USA. This will give you a clearer picture of the trend and the seasonal cycle. Since the data is monthly you will guess that the seasonality might be 12 time periods, however this won't always be the case.</p>
<p>The milk production time series has been loaded in to the DataFrame milk_production and is available in your environment.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Import the seasonal_decompose() function from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal.</li>
<li>Decompose the 'pounds_per_cow' column of milk_production using an additive model and period of 12 months.</li>
<li>Plot the decomposition.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">milk_production</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;./datasets/milk_production.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>  <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">])</span>
<span class="n">display</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">milk_production</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>&lt;class &#39;pandas.core.frame.DataFrame&#39;&gt;
DatetimeIndex: 168 entries, 1962-01-01 to 1975-12-01
Data columns (total 1 columns):
 #   Column          Non-Null Count  Dtype  
---  ------          --------------  -----  
 0   pounds_per_cow  168 non-null    float64
dtypes: float64(1)
memory usage: 2.6 KB
</pre>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_area">



<div class="output_text output_subarea ">
<pre>None</pre>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.tsa.seasonal</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">seasonal_decompose</span>

<span class="c1"># Perform additive decomposition</span>
<span class="n">decomp</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">seasonal_decompose</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">milk_production</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;pounds_per_cow&#39;</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">period</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot decomposition</span>
<span class="n">decomp</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">



<div class="output_png output_subarea ">
<img src="data:image/png;base64,"
>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>You have extracted the seasonal cycle and now you can see the trend much more clearly.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Seasonal ACF and PACF</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Below is a time series showing the estimated number of water consumers in London. By eye you can't see any obvious seasonal pattern, however your eyes aren't the best tools you have.</p>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/water_consumers.png" alt=""></p>
<p>In this exercise you will use the ACF and PACF to test this data for seasonality. You can see from the plot above that the time series isn't stationary, so you should probably detrend it. You will detrend it by subtracting the moving average. Remember that you could use a window size of any value bigger than the likely period.</p>
<p>The plot_acf() function has been imported and the time series has been loaded in as water.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Plot the ACF of the 'water_consumers' column of the time series up to 25 lags.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">

<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">water</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="SARIMA-models">SARIMA models<a class="anchor-link" href="#SARIMA-models"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Fitting SARIMA models</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Fitting SARIMA models is the beginning of the end of this journey into time series modeling.</p>
<p>It is important that you get to know your way around the SARIMA model orders and so that's what you will focus on here.</p>
<p>In this exercise, you will practice fitting different SARIMA models to a set of time series.</p>
<p>The time series DataFrames df1, df2 and df3 and the SARIMAX model class are available in your environment.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Create a SARIMAX(1,0,0)(1,1,0) model and fit it to df1.</li>
<li>Print the model summary table.</li>
<li>Create a SARIMAX(2,1,1)(1,0,0) model and fit it to df2.</li>
<li>Create a SARIMAX(1,1,0)(0,1,1) model and fit it to df3.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">df1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;./datasets/df1.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">])</span>
<span class="n">df2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;./datasets/df2.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">])</span>
<span class="n">df3</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;./datasets/df3.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">])</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df1</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">())</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">())</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df3</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Great! You have now got to grips with the seasonal and non-seasonal model orders. Did you notice how the parameters for the seasonal and non-seasonal AR and MA coefficients are printed in the results table?</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Choosing SARIMA order</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In this exercise you will find the appropriate model order for a new set of time series. This is monthly series of the number of employed persons in Australia (in thousands). The seasonal period of this time series is 12 months.</p>
<p>You will create non-seasonal and seasonal ACF and PACF plots and use the table below to choose the appropriate model orders/ <br></p>
<table>
<thead><tr>
<th></th>
<th>AR(p)</th>
<th>MA(q)</th>
<th>ARMA(p,q)</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>ACF</td>
<td>Tails off</td>
<td>Cuts off after lag q</td>
<td>Tails off</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>PACF</td>
<td>Cuts off after lag p</td>
<td>Tails off</td>
<td>Tails off</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><br></p>
<p>The DataFrame <code>aus_employment</code> and the functions <code>plot_acf()</code> and <code>plot_pacf()</code> are available in your environment.</p>
<p>Note that you can take multiple differences of a DataFrame using <code>df.diff(n1).diff(n2)</code>.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Take the first order difference and the seasonal difference of the aus_employment and drop the NaN values. The seasonal period is 12 months.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">plot_acf</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">plot_pacf</span>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Based on the ACF and PACF plots, which of these models is most likely for the data?</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>Answer:</strong> $ SARIMAX(0,1,0)(0,1,1)_{12} $
The non-seasonal ACF doesn't show any of the usual patterns of MA, AR or ARMA models so we choose none of these. The Seasonal ACF and PACF look like an MA(1) model. We select the model that combines both of these.</p>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>SARIMA vs ARIMA forecasts</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In this exercise, you will see the effect of using a SARIMA model instead of an ARIMA model on your forecasts of seasonal time series.</p>
<p>Two models, an $ARIMA(3,1,2)$ and a $ SARIMA(0,1,1)(1,1,1)_{12} $, have been fit to the Wisconsin employment time series. These were the best ARIMA model and the best SARIMA model available according to the AIC.</p>
<p>In the exercise you will use these two models to make dynamic future forecast for 25 months and plot these predictions alongside held out data for this period, wisconsin_test.</p>
<p>The fitted ARIMA results object and the fitted SARIMA results object are available in your environment as <code>arima_results</code> and <code>sarima_results</code>.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Create a forecast object, called arima_pred, for the ARIMA model to forecast the next 25 steps after the end of the training data.</li>
<li>Extract the forecast .predicted_mean attribute from arima_pred and assign it to arima_mean.</li>
<li>Repeat the above two steps for the SARIMA model.</li>
<li>Plot the SARIMA and ARIMA forecasts and the held out data wisconsin_test.</li>
</ul>
<p>CODE:</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Create ARIMA mean forecast</span>
<span class="n">arima_pred</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">arima_results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_forecast</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">25</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">arima_mean</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">arima_pred</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predicted_mean</span>

<span class="c1"># Create SARIMA mean forecast</span>
<span class="n">sarima_pred</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sarima_results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_forecast</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">25</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">sarima_mean</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sarima_pred</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predicted_mean</span>
<span class="c1"># Plot mean ARIMA and SARIMA predictions and observed</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">dates</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sarima_mean</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;SARIMA&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">dates</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">arima_mean</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;ARIMA&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">wisconsin_test</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;observed&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
<p><br>
Results:</p>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/arima_sarima.svg" alt=""></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>You can see that the SARIMA model has forecast the upward trend and the seasonal cycle, whilst the ARIMA model has only forecast the upward trend with an added wiggle. This makes the SARIMA forecast much closer to the truth for this seasonal data!</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Automation-and-saving">Automation and saving<a class="anchor-link" href="#Automation-and-saving"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Automated model selection</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The <code>pmdarima</code> package is a powerful tool to help you choose the model orders. You can use the information you already have from the identification step to narrow down the model orders which you choose by automation.</p>
<p>Remember, although automation is powerful, it can sometimes make mistakes that you wouldn't. It is hard to guess how the input data could be imperfect and affect the test scores.</p>
<p>In this exercise you will use the <code>pmdarima</code> package to automatically choose model orders for some time series datasets.</p>
<p>Be careful when setting the model parameters, if you set them incorrectly your session may time out.</p>
<p>Three datasets are available in your environment as df1, df2 and df3.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Import the pmdarima package as pm.</li>
<li>Model the time series df1 with period 7 days and set first order seasonal differencing and no non-seasonal differencing.</li>
<li>Create a model to fit df2. Set the non-seasonal differencing to 1, the trend to a constant and set no seasonality.</li>
<li>Fit a $ SARIMAX(p,1,q)(P,1,Q)_7$ model to the data setting <code>start_p</code>, <code>start_q</code>, <code>max_p</code>, <code>max_q</code>, <code>max_P</code> and <code>max_Q</code> to 1.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">df1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;./datasets/automation_df1.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">])</span>
<span class="n">df2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;./datasets/automation_df2.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">])</span>
<span class="n">df3</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;./datasets/automation_df3.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">])</span>

<span class="n">df1</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">freq</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">&#39;D&#39;</span>
<span class="n">df2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">freq</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">&#39;D&#39;</span>
<span class="n">df3</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">freq</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">&#39;D&#39;</span>

<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df1</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">())</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">())</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df3</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>We use the information we already know about the time series to predefine some of the orders before we fit. Automating the choice of orders can speed us up, but it needs to be done with care.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Saving and updating models</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Once you have gone through the steps of the Box-Jenkins method and arrived at a model you are happy with, you will want to be able to save that model and also to incorporate new measurements when they are available. This is key part of putting the model into production.</p>
<p>In this exercise you will save a freshly trained model to disk, then reload it to update it with new data.</p>
<p>The model is available in your environment as model.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Import the joblib package and use it to save the model to "candy_model.pkl".</li>
<li>Use the joblib package to load the model back in as loaded_model.</li>
<li>Update the loaded model with the data df_new.</li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<div class="highlight"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">joblib</span>

<span class="c1"># Set model name</span>
<span class="n">filename</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;candy_model.pkl&#39;</span>

<span class="c1"># Pickle it</span>
<span class="n">joblib</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dump</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">model</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">filename</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Load the model back in</span>
<span class="n">loaded_model</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">joblib</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">load</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">filename</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Update the model</span>
<span class="n">loaded_model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">update</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df_new</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>You've just updated an old model with new measurements. This means it will make better prediction of the future. The next step might be to make new predictions with this model or save the updated version back to the file.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="SARIMA-and-Box-Jenkins">SARIMA and Box-Jenkins<a class="anchor-link" href="#SARIMA-and-Box-Jenkins"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Multiplicative vs additive seasonality</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The first thing you need to decide is whether to apply transformations to the time series. In these last few exercises you will be working towards making a forecast of the CO time series. This and another time series for electricity production are plotted below.</p>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/co2_electricity.png" alt=""></p>
<p>Which of the above time series, if either, should be log transformed?</p>
<blockquote><p>Ans:Right plot: Electricity production.
Multiplicative seasonality is fairly common, and is important to be able to identify. You don't see it in the CO2 time series, so you won't apply the transform this time.</p>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>SARIMA model diagnostics</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Usually the next step would be to find the order of differencing and other model orders. However, this time it's already been done for you. The time series is best fit by a SARIMA(1, 1, 1)(0, 1, 1) model with an added constant.</p>
<p>In this exercise you will make sure that this is a good model by first fitting it using the SARIMAX class and going through the normal model diagnostics procedure.</p>
<p>The DataFrame, co2, and the SARIMAX model class are available in your environment.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Fit a $SARIMA(1, 1, 1)(0, 1, 1)_{12} $ model to the data and set the trend to constant.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">co2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;./datasets/co2_345.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">])</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">co2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>&lt;class &#39;pandas.core.frame.DataFrame&#39;&gt;
DatetimeIndex: 345 entries, 1990-01-01 to 2018-09-01
Data columns (total 1 columns):
 #   Column   Non-Null Count  Dtype  
---  ------   --------------  -----  
 0   CO2_ppm  345 non-null    float64
dtypes: float64(1)
memory usage: 5.4 KB
None
</pre>
</div>
</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">SARIMAX</span>

<span class="c1"># Create model object</span>
<span class="n">model</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">SARIMAX</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">co2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">order</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">seasonal_order</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">trend</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;c&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># Fit model</span>
<span class="n">results</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>In the console, print the summary of the results object you just created. Is there anything wrong with this model?</p>
<blockquote><p>Answer:None of the above.</p>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Create the common diagnostics plots for the results object.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_diagnostics</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">20</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_png output_subarea ">
<img src="data:image/png;base64,"
>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Examine the plot you just created. Is there anything wrong with this model?</p>
<blockquote><p>Ans:None of the above. the residuals look fine in these plots.</p>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>SARIMA forecast</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In the previous exercise you confirmed that a SARIMA  x  model was a good fit to the CO time series by using diagnostic checking.</p>
<p>Now its time to put this model into practice to make future forecasts. Climate scientists tell us that we have until 2030 to drastically reduce our CO emissions or we will face major societal challenges.</p>
<p>In this exercise, you will forecast the CO time series up to the year 2030 to find the CO levels if we continue emitting as usual.</p>
<p>The trained model results object is available in your environment as results.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Create a forecast object for the next 136 steps - the number of months until Jan 2030.</li>
<li>Assign the .predicted_mean of the forecast to the variable mean.</li>
<li>Compute the confidence intervals and assign this DataFrame to the variable conf_int</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">forecast_object</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">results</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_forecast</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">136</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Extract predicted mean attribute</span>
<span class="n">mean</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">forecast_object</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predicted_mean</span>

<span class="c1"># Calculate the confidence intervals</span>
<span class="n">conf_int</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">forecast_object</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">conf_int</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Extract the forecast dates</span>
<span class="n">dates</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mean</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Instructions: <br></p>
<ul>
<li>Plot the mean predictions against the dates.</li>
<li>Shade the area between the values in the first two columns of DataFrame conf_int using dates as the x-axis values.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot past CO2 levels</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">co2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">co2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;past&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot the prediction means as line</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">dates</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;predicted&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Shade between the confidence intervals</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fill_between</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">dates</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">conf_int</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[:,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;lower CO2_ppm&#39;</span><span class="p">],</span> 
                 <span class="n">conf_int</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[:,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;upper CO2_ppm&#39;</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">alpha</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.2</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot legend and show figure</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">



<div class="output_png output_subarea ">
<img src="data:image/png;base64,"
>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>
